text: Instagram || Twitter || Facebook || Amazon || PinterestPeople swear by this book; they want to make it their god. Well, if this book is a religion, then I'm an atheist, because there was absolutely nothing in this book I want to believe in. Did we all read the same book? Man, the author is lucky that books don't have hotlines where you can phone in to complain about your lack of customer satisfaction, because I'd be on the line right now, saying, "Dafuque-ce que c'est?" Comme ça.JELLICOE ROAD is an utterly nonsensical book that appears to thrive on its own pretension. Taylor, the main character, spends all of her time either whining or crying, and her biggest claim to fame is that she's in charge of this stupid mock-war her school fights with the locals and the local military school for "territory." If that sounds confusing, don't worry - it's never explained, it doesn't make sense, and it's just as childish and lame as it sounds. Oh, and she's in love with the local bad boy military student who ~betrayed~ her once, many a summer ago.Looped in with this Risk LARPing is the story of some other pretentious kids with ~issues~ who are connected with Taylor's story in a mysterious way. This other POV was incredibly boring and I skimmed it, and yes, the payoff was just as disappointing as I'd imagined it would be, and surprise, surprise, I was able to predict most of it. I'm guessing this is the part of the story that made people shed tears, but mostly I just thought it was lame. And pretentious.I guess if you want to read about the most boring LARP session ever with a tepid love story that makes TWILIGHT seem deep and profound by comparison, read this book. If you're looking for the profound and live-changing story that was beautifully written and so moving and unique, take me with you, because I finished this book and I didn't find that story. Maybe it's on the Jellicoe Road...1 star

Honest to God, I don't even know what the hell I read.Before I begin, you'll realize I've referred to this book as JelliNOE Road. Because that's what is: A NO.Don't ask me what this book is about, because 1) I don't know what it's about, and 2) I'd like to forget this book exists.Thank you. JelliNOE Road has been on my TBR for a while. I added it because MAYBELINE adores it. I only decided to pick it up last week because May and I had a deal. She fulfilled her part of the deal and me reading this book was fulfilling my part. LOOK HOW THAT TURNED OUT.If you love this book, I'm glad you did! But I highly doubt you want to continue reading this review.I'm aware I'm a minority here but I was literally suffering as I read this, because 1) Boring 2) Boring 3) Boring 4) Confusion level 10,000 6) HUH? 7) ????? 8) ?????, and 9) WHAT THE HELL IS GOING ON?Listen, I don't have a problem with confusing plots, as long as I at least get a tiny bit of sense of what's going on and it gets me hooked, but in JelliNOE Road... I don't even know, guys. NOPE. NOPE. NOPE. Literally, the only thing I can tell you about this book is what's written in the blurb and the characters' names. I started reading this book last week, but I was in a horrible slump, and apparently this book is not the best book to read during one. So, I stopped reading it for a few days while I fixed my slump. It was basically over beginning of this week and then I picked JelliNOE again two days ago. DID THINGS GET BETTER? NOPE.JelliNOOOOOOOOOE.Guys, please, someone tell me what was happening in this book. Why did everyone cry over it? What was the point? WHAT DID I MISS? This is actually stressful because I had high hopes???? AND NOW I JUST WANT TO BUY A PHYSICAL COPY SO I CAN THROW IT OUT OF MY DAMN WINDOW.Also, ZERO connection with the characters (Jonah was okay, but whatever). Our MC, Taylor... Queen of Whining and Crying. That's her new name.In conclusion, JelliNOE Road is my first AND last book by Melina Marchetta.
Gave up on 40%. Couldn't connect to the characters or the story, guess it was time to move on.

Every Filipino who loves his country must read this book.Reason: On April 13, 2012, North Korea's long-range rocket launched, failed. Reuters is now saying that, embarrassed by rocket crash, North Korea may now be thinking of trying nuclear test. Check the path and the trajectory plan of that failed rocket launch:

Do you see that tail-end of the yellow line? That's Luzon, the biggest island in the Philippines. That's where Manila is. That's where I live!But why should we read this book?Here's why:

He reads this book!Seriously, I am one of the moderators of The Filipino Group here in Goodreads. This book, Jellicoe Road by an Australian novelist, Melina Marchetta is our book of the month and we will have our face-to-face book discussion on Saturday. As a moderator and one of the senior members of the group, some members ask me what I think of the book. Even if they don't say or admit it, my views influence some of them. At this point, I guess my job is to encourage them to read the book and join the actual book discussion. That's why even if I did not like this book, I cannot rate this with 1 star. Why I did not like this book?1. I cannot understand why the first 100 pages should be made confusing2. The claim or fight for territory has nothing to do with the rest of the book. Also, I do not understand exactly how it is supposed to work.3. The love affair between Taylor and Briggs is too mushy for my taste. Felt like Katniss-Peeta or Bella-Edward. I'm too old for that.4. Taylor is a pathetic female character IMO.5. Taylor is asked to lead even if she is asthmatic. Is there nobody else who can lead?Anyway, according to my trusted friends in this group, the book is amazing. Maybe they are still young and the story "speaks" to them. So, let's leave it at that. However, I can say that this book has a good intent. It also has a developed story that other readers can emphatize with. I guess that this is just not for me. But it is my ardent desire that this book will influence our North Korean friend to back off in his evil plan of building nuclear arsenal in the side of the world. Stop your expansionist plan, please and be content on what you have. Then if you have to test nukes, please don't point it to the Philippines! See, we also love Melina Marchetta! See, we both read and enjoy this book! Thanks for lending me this book, Aaron.

What’s going on in this book? What genre is this book? After 150 pages I should at minimum know this, but no. Taylor goes to Jellicoe Road School. The School, the Cadets and the Townies are fighting an ongoing war. Is this a real war? Is this dystopian? Or is this supposed to be realistic fiction? Meanwhile, Marnie and Tate’s parents died in an auto crash on Jellicoe Road. Who—or what are they; ghosts, fictional characters, a different timeline? Where are the adults around all these kids? I’ve read three times what I usually read when I don’t care for a book. And it’s not that I didn’t like it, I’m just as confused by it on page 156 as I was when I opened it.

DNF 36%I have really, really great news. I can remove about four books from my TBR. This is the third time I've tried, and the third time I could not give a damn for this author's book. I've said before that outside of romance, I don't need to love/identify with/like my characters. It's really true. I enjoy books where I am completely, utterly separate. I can enjoy author's art without enjoying anything else about the book. And I was detached from this protagonist. She was unlikable. She was detached. And sometimes I even love those characters. But Marchetta's words don't make me care about what's happening, they don't have the clarity and the direction for me to invest in the story. And hold on your hats, unpopular opinion, I don't like her writing.*Ducks/deflects things being thrown*Definitely don't take my word on it, and from what I understand the back half of this book is like...magic. But it's too late friends, I don't care, and I don't think an author should get away with writing such a weird, confusing foundation without it being...the point? If it is the point...I should still care? Does this make sense? Probably not. You might want to check other reviews. I just called it because I'm sitting over here with a bored look on my face, actively disliking this book. And yep, after 3 experiences that left me like...oh....kay? I'm won't be reading her again.

Tried to read this book because it won an award, but I just couldn't get into it. I didn't care about the characters, didn't understand why I should care about what was happening, and it felt like the story was going nowhere. So, I didn't bother finishing it. Reading other reviews of this book, it seems like a lot of people say it takes about 100 pages to get into the story. I ask, why would I want to read 100 pages of a story I'm not enjoying to supposedly get to the heart of the story? Lame. What is it with award winning books sometimes being unreadable???

having a h-u-g-e problem with this book - one that seems to have plagued everyone else. i'm at my 100 page cutoff and it's mostly boring me. i love a good mystery and don't need everything spelled out for me (major Lost and BSG geek here), by any means, but there's a fine line between disparate plot points that are intriguing and captivating and those that are irritating and piss me right the hell off. and that fine line is an entirely personal thing.however, since such a massive amount of the reviewers rated it so highly while at the same time admitting that it takes 100 pages to get into it (although many say it takes another 30-50 *groan*) and have the pieces start falling together, i'll continue on for a bit . . . only a bit though, because it's not just the pieces that need to fall together, i gotta start liking at least one or more of these characters (besides the musically artistic Ben) stat!yeah, so . . . read another 100 and disliked it just as much if not more. so i did something i almost never do and literally flipped the pages, looking for anything to stick out. can i just say that one thing that did was another 90 pages later - still talking about the frakking territory wars and the clubhouse!! honestly?! then i went online and dug up the details of the story to fill in my skimming antics. interesting enough how they all collided and overlapped, IF the pace had been quickened, for me at least. thought the overdone mysteriousness of who those original kids were/are now was pretentious. now knowing what happened - it just seems melodramaticwhy the drama about the territory wars, making it sound post-apocalyptic or other-worldly? oh, that's right. so, people will be so enthralled by the unknown that they'll keep reading. not so much.and really, we've all been through struggles, but this girl Taylor was too much of an emotional wreck for me - get a grip, girlfriend. haven't been this irritated by a book in a long time. gonna have to grab something good from the library tomorrow to get the taste out of my mouth.

I bought this book as soon as it came out because I was expecting another 'Looking for Alibrandi' or 'Saving Francesca', which it definitely isn't. Melina Marchetta evidently decided when writing this to branch out and try some new things, which is great, but I didn't like the book and felt BETRAYED that she'd made that decision just when I'd decided I had enough faith in her to buy her books without reading them first. I found the whole ultra-mysterious 'brooding' tone pretentious and the romance between the characters was too melodramatic for my taste. Although I'm sure it will ring true for adolescent girls everywhere who will no doubt be all 'OMG I can totally relate to Taylor because she is like, so INTENSE and has had so much EMOTIONAL TRAUMA in her life, just like ME!'Besides that, though, I thought the mystery part of it was poorly done. A lot of people are saying in their reviews that they found it 'confusing', at least at first - and it is. There's a fine line between giving everything away and not revealing anything at all until the very end. When done correctly the reader is left guessing, but not frustrated. This, in my opinion, did not get the right balance.

Check it out from the library or borrow it from me.

"Read" and "finished" don't really apply, as I am opting to free myself from the shackles of this book at page 36, but if I can save one person from beginning it, this review serves its purpose. Plus, I wouldn't want to forget that I attempted it once and try a second time in my more senile years!Plot (as far as I can tell): Taylor goes to a weird military-seeming boarding school after being abandoned by her parents and is placed in charge of basically a fraternity/sorority of "underground" kids that think way too highly of themselves and put too much faith into speaking in code. There's a woman she's close to in the school and she dreams of being in love. I'm kind of in shock as to why I couldn't force myself to read it. I read rave reviews from revered Goodreads personalities and got the title from a list of "must reads" somewhere in the social media abyss, but unlike some of the reviewers, I found the prose heavy, murky, and droll. The flashbacks/internal thoughts mixed with the actions didn't flow, and I don't need over 300 pages of suffering to sift through it. Taylor didn't compel me to enjoy her character in any way, as she is a brat with a chip on her shoulder despite the advantages normal orphans wouldn't be offered. The worst aspect of all, however, had to be the jargon. I couldn't stand the mention of many artifacts that held no significance to me or any of the characters, like the "little purple book," and I didn't care to read anymore to learn! Instead of intriguing, it was just off-putting, much like how the narration didn't help the reader understand the weird townie vs. boarding school war. It was almost like an idea meant for an elementary audience, but "beefed up" to try to make it YA.I don't quit books often. In fact, I only remember quitting two others in the past five years, but I just couldn't go on, and this is someone who is completing a doctorate, has an M.A. in English, reads YA often, and teaches high school.

DNF at pg 106So... I gave Melina Marchetta another try to woo me... and guys... I REALLY wanted her to woo me. Wow me. Whoa me. Wake me. Anything (that preferably begins with a "w" and doesn't involve putting me to sleep. jk... but only on the "w" part.) besides another DNF. Welp. I really wanted to hop aboard the Melina Marchetta train, because it seems like everyone has, but then again... I remind myself that I am my own person, and there's no point in standing with a crowd you don't belong in. So, while I can see why many people adore her writing, I guess it just simply is not for me. The humor is a little too dry (like the desert) for my taste, her prose has a nice simplicity that makes it an easy read but I lean more to literary fiction (BUT I allot many exceptions), and what I think really gets me is the pace. I got to page 50 and was still wondering when something, ANYTHING, would happen. Where is the introduction of conflict? Action? Excitement? Maybe I missed it when my eyes glazed over somewhere between the flipping of said pages, but I earnestly tried to invest myself in this book, and when you have to work hard to do that... well it's not a promising sign. Even at page 100, I was still oblivious as to what the plot of this book was. Well, I'm sure many people will read 
Jellicoe Road
 and be instant converts. But overall, my feelings are sort of "meh" and "time for a nap".

As I said in one of my status updates, I was very upset by the fact that they lived in Australia. I wasn't expecting that and frankly I kind of hate books that are based in Australia. Like, Stolen. After reading The Disreputable History of Frankie... and The Mockingbirds , I became kind of disenchanted with the whole thing. It seemed, at first, that they girl's mother died on this notorious "Jellicoe Road" but then she talks about her like she's alive or something and I didn't understand. And then she was elected to be some kind of leader for some darn secret society and I started gagging because it reminded me of the darn books I mentioned above(the Frankie and mockingbirds one). I just didn't like it and when I read those dozen pages or whatever and sat it down, I knew that I wouldn't be picking it up again. I think a lot of people like this book and I'm not exactly sure why. This is one of those books that I didn't finish and that I have no regret doing so.

Could not get past preview. I like to get about 25% in before I decide I'm not going to continue on with a book. I didn't get that far with this one. The voice was hard to grasp and hold onto for me personally. As a writer I have learned there are three ways to disorient the reader straight off the bat. 1. A Dream- This book starts with a prologue (but begins chapter one by talking about a dream.)2. Prologue- Background info that is usually better told inside the story. A lot of people skip over prologues 3. Italics- The prologue itself was in italics. Not terrible but made me a little crazy. All three of these things together disoriented me about the beginning of the story, the character, and what was actually happening. The language was beautiful and I enjoyed the description of thought but without something to grab onto I was just floating through pretty sky without a destination.

I've liked Marchetta's other books, but I do not understand the acclaim surrounding this one. I started out confused and then when I figured out what was going on, I didn't care.

If you're looking for painfully overwrought, convoluted, dull-as-dirt, or a sure-fire cure for insomnia, this is it. A House leader, Taylor Markham, who can't seem to figure out anything, including where her mom is, how to order white toast and marmalade, or how to spell "Holy Bible." She has a love/hate relationship with Cadet Griggs. There's a "war" going on between the Jellicoe school where Taylor attends, the Cadets, and the Townies. Girl wonder Raffy, Taylor's sidekick, is in a snit. So is Jonah Griggs' sidekick, boy wonder Santangelo. Throw in"To Kill a Mockingbird" with Jem and Mrs. Dubose. Kenny Rogers and "Coward of the Country." (Oh, please.) A boy in a tree who visits Taylor in her dreams. An idiot who shoots at tin cans from a tree. Add a "Prayer Tree" with "messages" in its trunk. Poor pacing. A ridiculous, rambling plot and enough teen angst and adolescent whining to choke a camel. It goes downhill from there. Fast.If "Drama Queen" was an Olympic sport, Taylor Markham would bring home gold for Australia.What a load of crap.

I'm calling this a DNF, I just don't see what the big deal was. I didn't feel that there was much of a plot, or that I got to know the main character. It was just a bunch of teenage boarding school kids with too much time on their hands apparently. I was left with so many questions: what was the deal with the school? What was so special about this Jellicoe Road? Maybe I didn't real carefully enough, or far enough, but also what was the deal with Hannah? So there's this lady who lives on the edge of the school property and apparently not associated with the school but helps out with the younger kids. I don't know why this book was awarded the Printz award for "excellence in young adult literature." I didn't feel like it was well written either.

On the Jellicoe Road is a melodramatic and wearisome YA novel about a girl searching for her family. It’s a joyless and jarring book, with all kinds of ill-fitting elements rammed in together. The first half is mostly about school kids playing a trite game of “territory wars” in a small Australian town. The author treats the game with extreme seriousness and weight, but in reality it’s a mere trifle. The “war” only lasts for 6 weeks each year, there are no real consequences for breaching territory, there’s nothing at stake either externally or personally, the teens could easily seek help from their teachers at any time, and the main character, Taylor Markham, isn’t even all that invested in the banal “war.” Taylor’s got other, more important things to worry about like having been abandoned by her drug addict mother as a child, and having witnessed a man kill himself via a rifle to the head (described with brain chunks and all. Ew!). As a result, the so-called war is little more than a bunch of pathetic, foolish children having hammy, soap opera-style confrontations and saying “You can’t go there, or else…!” for over a hundred pages. Oh, there’s an occasional punch, but it’s nothing to get worked up about. To make matters worse, eventually even the characters realise how pointless the “war” is and abandon the entire thing in an anticlimactic whimper. When even the characters think the central plot is boring and meaningless, that’s a sure sign to the author that her book needs to go back to rewrite. Apart from the so-called war, the book also features flashbacks to a group of teens 20 years ago, and explores Taylor’s search for identity and family. The flashbacks aren’t all that successful, chiefly because the past characters experience some serious, serious trauma that makes the present-day story seem even more lightweight and meaningless. For example, one repeated flashback depicts a girl surviving an horrific car crash and watching her mother getting decapitated right before her eyes. (Again, ew! Such exceedingly grotesque images are tonally jarring). How on earth are we supposed to care one iota about Taylor Markham’s schoolyard rivalries after reading that?Taylor Markham’s search for identity is not particularly involving either. Taylor is obviously hurting from the separation from her mother and yearning for some sort of connection – that’s fine. But Taylor is a histrionic drama queen who reacts to every minor problem in her life by screaming. Emotion-wise, there’s no perceptible difference between Taylor being abandoned by her mother as a child and Taylor having a petty argument with her sorta, kinda boyfriend. Apart from making Taylor unlikeable, this strips all the impact from the actually serious, life-changing events in the book. Moreover, because so much of the book is taken up by the tiresome non-war, everything else is left rushed and underdeveloped. This book is unrealistically over-stuffed with some truly HEAVY topics. Apart from the traumatic car crash and suicide scenes, there’s also paedophilia, child prostitution, homelessness, drug addiction, cancer, mental illness, attempted suicide, accidental death, a fire... But these big events aren't explored with much in the way of depth or subtlety. There simply isn't space in the book for that. Some of these events come across as exploitative, as though they were included simply to shock the reader. Others come across as excessively sentimental melodrama.Not to mention, it’s all incredibly predictable. Like, golly gosh, do you suppose there might be some sort of link between the present and past stories?! Golly gosh, could Taylor Markham’s search for family possibly lead her to the group of teens featured in the flashbacks?! Every time a link is “revealed,” I literally groaned in frustration because it was SO BLOODY OBVIOUS. I wouldn’t usually complain about this, except that the author uses such flimsy, bald-faced plot devices to artificially extend Taylor’s search for her family. Like, Taylor has been cared for by a woman who knows the whole story, but chosen not to say anything for positively no discernible reason. And Taylor discovers a manuscript depicting the events on the teens 20 years ago – but it is conveniently unfinished and then stolen before she can read it all. Not to mention that Taylor has conveniently forgotten or repressed the memory of every significant event in her life – until the opportune moment when her memory suddenly returns(!). And isn’t it a tad unbelievable that 
all
 the characters were known by completely different names as teenagers? These contrivances had me rolling my eyes. I just couldn’t become engaged with the story because the way it unfolds was so nonsensical. Oh, and there’s also this totally random serial killer subplot that, unsurprisingly, goes nowhere. That sentence plainly has nothing to do with anything previously mentioned in this paragraph, but the serial killer subplot plainly has nothing to do with anything in this book.The bottom line is this book was an absolute chore to read. I will gladly admit that there are some fleeting, isolated scenes that were dramatically effective and for that reason I can kinda understand why some readers absolutely love this book. For example, there's what might be the perfect teen sex scene - a scene that manages to be both emotionally intense but also painfully realistic. But for me there was just too much padding in this book for me to give it anything other than a 1 out of 5. With absolute honesty, when I finished this book I was downright relieved I didn’t have to put up with any more of Taylor Markham’s crap.

Además, alternar entre pasado y presente aporta un ritmo más ágil.No recurre a excesivas descripciones, pero sí aporta datos de la trama que poco a poco irán conectando. La historia se me ha hecho bastante aburrida, pues tardó mucho en despertar un interés en mí que se volvería a ir rápidamente. Esperaba una historia profunda y ha resultado ser bastante plana para mi gusto.

Reading through chapter 12 (page 140 out of 400), I was so utterly bored that I decided to give up, literally mid-sentence. And I don’t quit books easily. However, at 35% percent into the story, the writer should have provided a general overview, but this novel was entirely directionless. Without the blurb, I would not have had a clue what is going on. This scene threw me off: a panel of senior students from a boarding school discussing territorial rights with the leaders of the local school kids and a neighbouring military school. In fact, the council is about access to waterways - as if any of them had any actual claim to the land. This territorial dispute is never even properly explained. The novel seems to have two main characters. On the one hand, there is Taylor, now 17 [I will never understand the trend to upgrade occupations into female first names], who at 11 was abandoned by her mother at a petrol station, and at 14 tried to run away from said boarding school to find her mother. On the run, she somehow fraternized with Jonah, a "Cadet" and now her antagonist. However, this backstory is structured as one big secret with only morsels of information thrown in. Taylor is also a particularly mopey, unappealing character. Yawn. Then there is Hannah, a woman in her 30s who survived a car crash as a child. She lives on the school premises and is Taylor’s friend. Somehow she is a main character, even though she has been missing since page 1. Again, lots of mysterious hints. Apparently, at the end you find out how all the events and characters are connected to each other. But I obviously don’t care to find out. I don’t know why this book is so successful. It’s just so dull. So, goodbye.

I would like to know who was on the Printz committee the year this book was selected as the winner, because SERIOUSLY, it was all over the place, and not in a good way. I listened to this book on audio, so I would like to think that it might have made more sense if I had read it, but probably not.Like many other reviewers, I found the first third of the book to be extremely confusing. There are "border wars" between the kids from the Jellicoe school, the townies, and the cadets. For the longest time I couldn't decipher if these wars were serious and spoke to the setting, or if they were just child's play. When it became evident that the adults in the story didn't know about the border wars, I stopped caring because the border wars were obviously just some added element that didn't really serve a purpose or move the plot forward. Next was the "manuscript" that the chapters alternate back and forth between. This did not translate well into the audio book at all and for the record, THERE WERE TOO MANY DAMN CHARACTERS. I couldn't keep track of all the kids in the manuscript and all the kids in present tense. It seemed to me that the manuscript gave Taylor (MC) an omniscient advantage, but then at the same time, how could she not realize that the kids from the manuscript were related to her, especially when she seemed to know so much about them. Learning about these characters via their pasts just didn't work well--there was too much of a disconnect.And the hermit. Once we find out who he is, there's still no explanation as to why he shot himself (with a shotgun--is that possible?) right in front of Taylor. Again, this element was just a sensational idea that served no purpose.I think the take away from this book is that connections are important, family or otherwise, but the message was overshadowed with so many other frivolous happenings and dead end ideas. I did not enjoy this book at all and couldn't wait for it to be over. I'm sure there were many other more deserving novels for the Printz award that year.

The summary on the book that I got however said:Abandoned by her mother on Jellicoe Road when she was eleven, Taylor Markham, now seventeen, is finally being confronted with her past. But as the reluctant leader of her boarding school dorm, there isn't a lot of time for introspection. And while Hannah, the closest adult Taylor has to family, had disappeared, Jonah Griggs is back in town, moody stares and all.It doesn't seem like it's that interesting, to me anyway. She's being made a leader? How does that happen? There's different people that elect her as a leader? Do the dorm-mates elect?Why are the adults so fucking useless that they don't know about this cult thing?Why is Taylor such a bitch?She makes me want to roll my eyes at this stuff. This book was incredibly dull, and I wish I had given up after the first one hundred pages instead of continuing to read like the reviews on goodreads told me to.First of all, one hundred pages is about fifty too many to keep your audience in the dark. Definitely the only reason it was added was so Taylor could fall in love with one of her enemies.Speaking of falling in love, I did not feel any kind of love between Taylor and Jonah. Maybe there was just too much else going on in the book, but in any case, if it's a big enough plot point to put on the summary on the back cover, it's a big enough plot point to actually make seem realistic.I regret buying this book.
